research/history_archive/history_20260320_152535/logs/agent_action_0008.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"At fixed K=128, a Hadamard-rotated factorized_topk SAE with a narrow nonlinear hidden mixing stage will beat the current rotated linear top-k proxy anchor on FVU by giving the encoder more expressive support selection than a single linear projection, without changing the fixed-K decode path.","summary":"Add a new factorized_topk prototype under sparsify/ and run it as a proxy at K=128 with Hadamard and the baseline signum optimizer. This is a quality-first architecture exploration step after the residual_topk stabilization regression, so the next move is a different higher-expressivity encoder family rather than another weak local sweep.","change_type":"edit_sae_code","experiment_tier":"proxy","expected_win":"lower_fvu","family_name":"factorized_topk","family_stage":"prototype","self_review":"This follows research/program.md: one coherent hypothesis, proxy by default, and architecture exploration after a normal-health residual_topk follow-up regressed. The implementation stays entirely under sparsify/, preserves the fixed execution layer, and passed a local instantiation plus forward/backward sanity check. The main risk is that the added nonlinearity may make optimization harder under signum, so a weak first proxy would argue for either optimizer-specific stabilization or abandoning this family quickly.","needs_sanity":true,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"factorized_topk"},{"key":"K","value":"128"},{"key":"USE_HADAMARD","value":"1"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"}],"touched_files":["sparsify/config.py","sparsify/sparse_coder.py","sparsify/__init__.py","sparsify/factorized_topk_sparse_coder.py"],"notes_to_memory":["Read research/program.md before deciding; after the residual_topk stabilization pass regressed under normal runtime, the right next move is a new quality-first architecture family rather than more narrow local tuning.","No operator_hints were present in the structured context for this round.","Added a factorized_topk prototype that inserts a narrow nonlinear hidden projection before latent scoring, keeping the standard decoder and fixed-K top-k interface intact.","Local sanity check passed for factorized_topk: Python instantiation plus forward/backward succeeded on a toy tensor, so the family is compatible with the existing SparseCoder training path."],"next_hypotheses":["If factorized_topk shows promising proxy FVU, keep the family alive with a stabilization pass over optimizer or orthogonality regularization before considering any smaller-K search.","If factorized_topk improves quality but shows a runtime regression, follow with an edit_perf_code pass on the extra hidden projection path instead of discarding the family.","If factorized_topk is clearly weak on proxy FVU, move on to a different higher-expressivity family such as a wider routed or multi-branch encoder rather than continuing local sweeps."]}
research/history_archive/history_20260320_152535/round_summaries/round_0004.json:51:        "key": "ARCHITECTURE",
research/history_archive/history_20260320_152535/logs/agent_action_0007.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"The current residual_topk prototype is likely capped by its fixed half-and-half latent budget: each branch can only nominate roughly K/2 features before the final merge, so the better branch cannot claim more of the final support even when it should. Letting both branches over-propose up to K candidates and then selecting the final global top-K from their union should preserve the residual design while removing this allocation bottleneck, improving FVU at fixed K=128.","summary":"Stabilize the promoted residual_topk family with a narrow architecture edit: remove the fixed per-branch K split so both the base and residual branches can each propose up to K candidates before the final global top-K selection. Run this as a proxy quality-first comparison at K=128 with the existing Hadamard+signum setup to test whether the family had been artificially capacity-limited.","change_type":"edit_sae_code","experiment_tier":"proxy","expected_win":"lower_fvu","family_name":"residual_topk","family_stage":"stabilize","self_review":"This stays within one coherent hypothesis and follows the program guidance to keep pushing a promising family before chasing smaller K or cost. I kept the execution layer unchanged, edited only sparsify/, and avoided mixing in optimizer or regularization sweeps so the result isolates the branch-allocation change. The main risk is extra duplicate candidates across branches with no quality gain, but the local forward/backward sanity check passed and runtime cost should remain close enough for a proxy read.","needs_sanity":true,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"residual_topk"},{"key":"K","value":"128"},{"key":"USE_HADAMARD","value":"1"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"}],"touched_files":["sparsify/residual_topk_sparse_coder.py"],"notes_to_memory":["Read research/program.md before deciding and respected the quality-first objective; with residual_topk newly promoted and still far from the aggressive target, a family-specific stabilization edit is more justified than smaller-K search.","No operator_hints were present in the structured context for this round.","Updated residual_topk so both branches can each propose up to K candidates before the final global top-k, removing the previous fixed half-and-half branch budget that could cap the family.","Local sanity check passed after the edit: residual_topk still instantiates and runs forward/backward successfully on a toy tensor."],"next_hypotheses":["If oversubscribed residual_topk improves proxy FVU, promote to full and then test residual_topk-specific stabilization such as ortho_lambda or Adam without changing K.","If quality improves but throughput regresses, follow with an edit_perf_code pass focused on the residual branch merge path rather than discarding the family.","If this edit does not improve residual_topk meaningfully, move to a different higher-expressivity family such as a factorized or wider multi-branch routed encoder instead of continuing narrow local sweeps."]}
research/history_archive/history_20260320_152535/round_summaries/round_0005.json:54:        "key": "ARCHITECTURE",
research/history_archive/history_20260320_152535/logs/agent_action_0002.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"At fixed K=128, a Hadamard-rotated JumpReLU encoder with a nontrivial learned threshold will suppress weak nuisance activations before top-k selection, improving support precision enough to beat the rotated topk anchor on proxy FVU.","summary":"Run a proxy prototype for a rotated JumpReLU family at K=128. This keeps the quality-first anchor fixed while testing whether thresholded sparse activation can materially outperform rotated topk, instead of spending another round on a likely weak local topk sweep.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"proxy","expected_win":"lower_fvu","family_name":"rotated_jumprelu","family_stage":"prototype","self_review":"This respects the fixed execution layer and uses only env overrides against an already-supported architecture family. It is a single coherent quality-first bet at K=128, which matches the program's guidance to escalate from modest rotated-topk gains into architecture exploration. The main risk is threshold miscalibration: if the initial threshold is too low JumpReLU may collapse toward topk, while if it is too high it may over-prune useful features. Proxy is the right place to test viability before any family-specific stabilization.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"jumprelu"},{"key":"K","value":"128"},{"key":"USE_HADAMARD","value":"1"},{"key":"JUMPRELU_INIT_THRESHOLD","value":"0.02"},{"key":"JUMPRELU_BANDWIDTH","value":"0.01"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["Round 2 escalates from modest rotated-topk improvement into a new encoder family rather than continuing local topk tuning.","The current codebase already supports JumpReLU through env overrides, so this prototype can be tested without touching the execution layer.","No operator_hints were present in structured context for this round."],"next_hypotheses":["If rotated JumpReLU shows promising proxy FVU but unstable optimization, keep the family alive with an optimizer-focused stabilization pass such as Adam or LR retuning.","If rotated JumpReLU improves quality but is still far from the aggressive target, sweep its threshold and bandwidth as the next family-specific stabilization step.","If rotated JumpReLU fails to show useful quality signal, move to a different encoder family with stronger routing expressivity rather than returning to weak local topk search."]}
research/history_archive/history_20260320_152535/logs/agent_action_0005.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"The routed_group_topk proxy crash was caused by an optimizer implementation bug, not by the architecture itself: ScheduleFreeWrapperReference writes per-parameter state before delegating to Adam, which makes Adam skip its own state initialization and crash on step 2. If Adam is run without the incompatible wrapper, the same rotated routed_group_topk prototype at K=128 should finally produce a usable quality signal and may beat the rotated topk proxy anchor on FVU.","summary":"Fix the Adam path in sparsify/trainer.py so proxy experiments can run routed_group_topk with Adam without crashing, then rerun the same rotated routed_group_topk prototype at K=128 to get an actual quality read instead of discarding the family on an implementation artifact.","change_type":"edit_sae_code","experiment_tier":"proxy","expected_win":"explore_unknown","family_name":"rotated_routed_group_topk","family_stage":"prototype","self_review":"This follows the program guidance to treat recent crashes as implementation issues before drawing architecture conclusions. The edit is narrowly scoped under sparsify/, preserves the fixed execution layer, and keeps one coherent hypothesis: unblocking Adam for the same family/config that previously failed before producing metrics. The main risk is that routed_group_topk may still underperform on quality once it runs, but this round cleanly separates that question from the optimizer bug.","needs_sanity":true,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"routed_group_topk"},{"key":"K","value":"128"},{"key":"USE_HADAMARD","value":"1"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"adam"},{"key":"LR","value":"3e-4"},{"key":"NUM_GROUPS","value":"32"},{"key":"ACTIVE_GROUPS","value":"8"}],"touched_files":["sparsify/trainer.py"],"notes_to_memory":["Read research/program.md before deciding; the right response to the last round is a code fix because the routed_group_topk run crashed before yielding any architectural evidence.","The round 4 crash is reproducibly explained by an optimizer bug: ScheduleFreeWrapperReference populates per-parameter state keys (z/x/y) before calling Adam, so Adam sees a non-empty state dict and then throws KeyError on missing exp_avg.","Updated sparsify/trainer.py so Adam uses a plain torch.optim.Adam path while SignSGD keeps the ScheduleFree wrapper; this preserves the existing signum behavior and unblocks Adam-based family exploration."],"next_hypotheses":["If routed_group_topk now runs and shows promising proxy FVU, keep the family alive with a stabilization sweep over num_groups, active_groups, and LR.","If routed_group_topk now runs but is clearly weak on proxy FVU, escalate to a different encoder family such as a factorized or multi-branch routed encoder instead of spending more rounds on weak local tuning.","If additional optimizer-specific issues appear for Adam-based families, isolate them as implementation bugs before interpreting the quality result."]}
research/history_archive/history_20260320_152535/logs/agent_action_0001.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"At fixed K=128, enabling Hadamard rotation on the baseline topk SAE will reduce FVU by spreading outlier energy across input dimensions, giving a stronger quality anchor before any lower-K search.","summary":"Run a proxy anchor-refresh experiment that keeps the standard topk SAE at K=128 and turns on Hadamard preprocessing. This is a parameter-only quality-first bet aimed at improving the baseline FVU without conflating the result with smaller K or a new encoder family.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"proxy","expected_win":"lower_fvu","family_name":"rotated_topk","family_stage":"mainline","self_review":"This stays within the fixed execution layer, makes no code edits, keeps K anchored at 128, and isolates one quality-focused change with plausible upside. The main risk is that Hadamard helps throughput/outlier handling more than reconstruction quality, but it is still the cleanest high-upside baseline refresh available from the current code surface.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"topk"},{"key":"K","value":"128"},{"key":"USE_HADAMARD","value":"1"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["Round 0 chose a quality-first K=128 anchor refresh instead of rewarding smaller K.","The current sparsify code already supports Hadamard-rotated topk SAE through env overrides, so this can be tested without code changes.","No operator_hints were present in structured context for this round."],"next_hypotheses":["If rotated topk materially improves proxy FVU, stabilize that family with optimizer and regularization sweeps before considering smaller K.","If rotated topk does not improve enough, escalate to a new encoder family rather than continuing weak local tuning around vanilla topk.","If rotated topk improves quality but shows poor runtime, follow with a performance-focused pass instead of discarding the direction."]}
research/history_archive/history_20260320_152535/logs/agent_action_0006.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"At fixed K=128, a Hadamard-rotated residual_topk SAE will beat the rotated topk proxy anchor on FVU by letting a second encoder pass allocate support on the first-pass reconstruction residual, reducing one-shot top-k competition without changing the execution layer.","summary":"Add a new residual_topk prototype under sparsify/ and run it at K=128 with Hadamard and the baseline signum optimizer. This is a quality-first architecture exploration step after routed_group_topk produced a clearly weak proxy result under normal runtime, so the next move is a new family rather than another local sweep.","change_type":"edit_sae_code","experiment_tier":"proxy","expected_win":"lower_fvu","family_name":"residual_topk","family_stage":"prototype","self_review":"This follows research/program.md: one coherent hypothesis, proxy by default, and architecture exploration after several non-improving rounds. The implementation is narrowly scoped under sparsify/ and passed a local instantiation plus forward/backward sanity check. The main risk is that splitting support across two passes could underuse the shared dictionary or create duplicate selections, so a weak proxy result would argue against this family rather than against residual-style search in general.","needs_sanity":true,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"residual_topk"},{"key":"K","value":"128"},{"key":"USE_HADAMARD","value":"1"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"}],"touched_files":["sparsify/config.py","sparsify/sparse_coder.py","sparsify/__init__.py","sparsify/residual_topk_sparse_coder.py"],"notes_to_memory":["Read research/program.md before deciding; with repeated non-improvements and a normal-health but weak routed_group_topk result, this round should explore a new quality-first family rather than another narrow sweep.","No operator_hints were present in the structured context for this round.","Added a residual_topk prototype that runs a second top-k encoder pass on the first-branch residual and then selects the final K latents from the union of both branches' candidates.","Local sanity check passed for residual_topk: Python instantiation plus forward/backward succeeded on a toy tensor, so the family is compatible with the existing SparseCoder training path."],"next_hypotheses":["If residual_topk shows promising proxy FVU, keep the family alive with a stabilization pass over optimizer or orthogonality regularization before considering any smaller-K search.","If residual_topk improves quality but shows throughput regressions, follow with a performance-focused pass instead of discarding the architecture.","If residual_topk is clearly weak on proxy FVU, move on to another encoder family such as a factorized or wider multi-branch routed encoder rather than spending more rounds on local tuning."]}
research/history_archive/history_20260320_152535/logs/agent_action_0003.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"At fixed K=128, a Hadamard-rotated gated SAE will beat rotated topk on proxy FVU by decoupling support selection from coefficient magnitude, giving the encoder a more expressive and fully differentiable routing mechanism than the failed rotated JumpReLU prototype.","summary":"Run a proxy prototype for a rotated gated SAE at K=128. This is a quality-first architecture exploration step that keeps the improved Hadamard preprocessing from the current anchor while testing whether independent gate and magnitude branches can materially improve reconstruction before any effort is spent on smaller K or cost reduction.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"proxy","expected_win":"lower_fvu","family_name":"rotated_gated","family_stage":"prototype","self_review":"This respects the fixed execution layer, uses only supported env overrides, and makes one coherent bet: stronger encoder expressivity at the same K=128 quality anchor. Gated is a better next family than group_topk because its selector is differentiable, whereas the current group_topk implementation explicitly notes ineffective router training. The main risk is that sigmoid gating may need optimizer retuning or longer warmup, so a weak proxy result would not fully rule the family out.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"gated"},{"key":"K","value":"128"},{"key":"USE_HADAMARD","value":"1"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["Read research/program.md before deciding; it reinforces a quality-first proxy default and encourages architecture exploration when local parameter search is not closing the gap.","The current sparsify code already supports gated SAE through env overrides, so this family can be tested without touching the execution layer.","GroupTopK is currently implemented with hard non-differentiable routing, so gated is the cleaner next routing-style family to test for quality."],"next_hypotheses":["If rotated gated shows promising proxy FVU but unstable optimization, keep the family alive with an optimizer-focused stabilization pass such as Adam or LR retuning.","If rotated gated improves quality but remains far from the aggressive target, sweep its regularization or related training settings before considering smaller K.","If rotated gated fails to show useful quality signal, escalate to a more novel encoder family or code-level architecture change rather than returning to weak local topk tuning."]}
research/history_archive/07_20260321_004359/logs/agent_action_0019.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"The round-18 refined_topk crash was caused by a mixed-precision implementation bug in the ridge solve, not by evidence against the architecture. Running the small support-wise solve in float32 and casting the refined coefficients back to the model dtype should make the family trainable under bf16 autocast, allowing a valid proxy read on whether coefficient refitting can lower FVU at K=128.","summary":"Keep refined_topk alive for one crash-recovery follow-up. The architecture stays the same, but its coefficient-refinement solve is now executed in a stable float32 path so the proxy run can test the actual quality hypothesis instead of failing on dtype mismatch.","change_type":"edit_sae_code","experiment_tier":"proxy","expected_win":"lower_fvu","family_name":"refined_topk","family_stage":"stabilize","self_review":"This is a narrow implementation-fix round on the most recent crashing family, which is the right move after a first-run failure with a clear stack trace. The main risk is that the architecture may still be weak even after the fix, but a clean rerun is more informative than abandoning the family based on a bf16/autocast bug.","needs_sanity":true,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"refined_topk"},{"key":"K","value":"128"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"8"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"adam"}],"touched_files":["/root/sparsify-ascend/sparsify/refined_topk_sparse_coder.py"],"notes_to_memory":["Round 19 fixes a refined_topk mixed-precision bug: the support-wise ridge solve now runs in float32 and casts refined coefficients back to the model dtype.","The refined_topk crash in round 18 came from a bf16/float32 mismatch inside torch.linalg.solve under autocast, so that round should not be treated as architecture evidence.","A local bf16 import/forward/backward sanity check passed for the fixed refined_topk implementation before handing control back to the runtime."],"next_hypotheses":["If the fixed refined_topk yields a meaningful proxy FVU gain, follow with a family-specific stabilization pass on regularization strength or support source before considering promotion.","If refined_topk now runs normally but lands near the recent 0.275 proxy plateau, conclude that coefficient refitting alone is insufficient and pivot to a genuinely different encoder family next round."]}
research/history_archive/07_20260321_004359/logs/agent_action_0003.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"A residual two-branch encoder may reduce FVU at K=128 by letting the second encoder pass target what the first branch misses, which is directly aligned with the reconstruction objective. Test residual_topk at the same K=128 anchor point as a quality-first architecture probe.","summary":"mixture_topk was slightly worse than the topk anchor under normal runtime, so the next move is to try a different expressive family rather than spending another round on that branch. residual_topk is the most directly FVU-oriented next architecture because it explicitly allocates encoder capacity to residual errors.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"proxy","expected_win":"lower_fvu","family_name":"residual_topk","family_stage":"prototype","self_review":"This keeps the comparison clean and opens a new family with a stronger direct link to reconstruction quality than mixture routing. It is still a first prototype pass, so a mediocre result should not automatically rule out all multi-branch encoders.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"residual_topk"},{"key":"K","value":"128"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"8"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["mixture_topk at K=128/ef8/signum archived under normal runtime with proxy FVU 0.3058621361851692, so soft expert mixing is not an immediate win over the anchor.","Round 3 opens residual_topk as a new quality-first family because its second encoder pass is explicitly aimed at reducing remaining reconstruction error."],"next_hypotheses":["If residual_topk shows proxy improvement, follow with a stabilization pass on optimizer or expansion factor before promotion.","If residual_topk is also flat or worse, try factorized_topk next rather than returning to smaller-K search."]}
research/history_archive/07_20260321_004359/logs/agent_action_0009.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"hybrid_topk with Adam is now the strongest K=128 configuration, so the next quality-first move is to increase representational capacity rather than shrink K or chase cost. Test hybrid_topk at K=128 with Adam and expansion_factor=16 to see whether extra latent capacity can materially reduce FVU again.","summary":"The hybrid_topk Adam stabilization produced a meaningful full improvement to 0.1619 FVU, but that is still far from the aggressive target. This round keeps the best family and optimizer fixed and spends one proxy run on a larger expansion factor as the cleanest quality-first scaling test.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"proxy","expected_win":"lower_fvu","family_name":"hybrid_topk","family_stage":"stabilize","self_review":"This is the right next bet because the current mainline finally has momentum and deserves capacity scaling before any lower-K or cost tradeoffs. The main risk is that extra capacity may give only marginal quality gains relative to added memory and compute.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"hybrid_topk"},{"key":"K","value":"128"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"16"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"adam"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["hybrid_topk plus Adam improved the full K=128 frontier to FVU 0.16189537942409515 with no runtime regression relative to the prior hybrid run.","Round 9 escalates capacity within the leading family by testing expansion_factor=16 at fixed K=128 and Adam before considering any lower-K or cost-driven moves."],"next_hypotheses":["If hybrid_topk with Adam and expansion_factor=16 improves proxy FVU, promote it to full as the new mainline quality candidate.","If the larger expansion factor is flat or only marginally better, keep hybrid_topk as mainline and look for a more targeted architectural improvement rather than scaling capacity further."]}
research/history_archive/07_20260321_004359/logs/agent_action_0011.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"A thresholded sparse activation family may beat the current hybrid mainline by learning which latent logits should be suppressed before top-k selection rather than only reshaping logits with extra branches. Test jumprelu at K=128 with Adam as a fresh quality-first family probe.","summary":"The latest hybrid_topk edit was a normal-runtime regression, and several rounds have now been spent on local hybrid stabilization without another gain. This round shifts back to architecture exploration with an untried family whose learned thresholds could improve selectivity at the same K=128 anchor point.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"proxy","expected_win":"explore_unknown","family_name":"jumprelu","family_stage":"prototype","self_review":"This is a deliberate reset to a genuinely different sparse activation mechanism after the hybrid local edits stalled. The risk is that JumpReLU may proxy poorly under the fixed-K implementation, but it is the cleanest untried family with a credible path to lower FVU.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"jumprelu"},{"key":"K","value":"128"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"8"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"adam"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["The best current full frontier remains hybrid_topk with Adam at K=128, expansion_factor=8, FVU 0.16189537942409515.","Round 11 reopens architecture exploration after hybrid local edits stalled, using jumprelu as a new family with learned thresholding at fixed K=128."],"next_hypotheses":["If jumprelu shows a strong proxy signal, promote it to full before doing more hybrid tuning.","If jumprelu is flat or worse, keep hybrid_topk Adam ef=8 as mainline and then decide between a new encoder family or a training-dynamics experiment on the hybrid checkpoint."]}
research/history_archive/07_20260321_004359/logs/agent_action_0004.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"A factorized nonlinear encoder may lower FVU at K=128 by adding a hidden mixing stage before latent scoring, giving the encoder more expressive feature composition while keeping the fixed-K decode path unchanged. Test factorized_topk at the same K=128 anchor point as the next quality-first family.","summary":"Both mixture_topk and residual_topk archived under normal runtime with proxy FVU near the topk proxy anchor, so the next move is another architecture family rather than smaller-K search. factorized_topk is the clearest remaining low-friction expressivity upgrade in the current codebase.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"proxy","expected_win":"lower_fvu","family_name":"factorized_topk","family_stage":"prototype","self_review":"This is still exploratory, but it continues the right search pattern: hold K fixed, change one architectural idea, and see whether encoder expressivity can move proxy FVU. If this also comes back flat, the current built-in families are not yet showing a path to the target.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"factorized_topk"},{"key":"K","value":"128"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"8"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["residual_topk at K=128/ef8/signum archived under normal runtime with proxy FVU 0.3055884689092636, so the residual two-branch prototype did not improve on the anchor.","Round 4 opens factorized_topk as the next expressive family to test at fixed K=128 before considering lower-K or cost-driven moves."],"next_hypotheses":["If factorized_topk improves proxy FVU, follow with a stabilization pass on optimizer or expansion factor before promotion.","If factorized_topk is also flat or worse, shift from parameter-only family swapping to a code edit that introduces a genuinely new encoder family or materially changes one incubating family."]}
research/history_archive/07_20260321_004359/logs/agent_action_0020.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"Crash recovery and policy both point to a narrow param-only move: keep the current best working proxy configuration in hybrid_topk fixed and test whether it remains viable when K is reduced from 128 to 64. This is the required first step in K exploration, and it isolates the effect of sparsity level without confounding architecture or optimizer changes.","summary":"Run a proxy K=64 check on the current best working hybrid_topk configuration, holding the rest of the known-stable proxy settings fixed so this round cleanly measures the first smaller-K point.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"proxy","expected_win":"explore_unknown","family_name":"hybrid_topk","family_stage":"stabilize","self_review":"This follows the runtime constraints exactly: no code edits, one coherent hypothesis, proxy-first, and explicit K exploration after recent crashes. I am using the best working proxy anchor rather than introducing any new family or secondary tuning, so the result should be interpretable even if K=64 regresses.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"hybrid_topk"},{"key":"K","value":"64"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"16"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"adam"},{"key":"LR","value":"8e-4"},{"key":"HOOKPOINTS","value":"layers.[3].self_attn.o_proj"},{"key":"BATCH_SIZE","value":"1"},{"key":"GRAD_ACC_STEPS","value":"8"},{"key":"MICRO_ACC_STEPS","value":"1"},{"key":"AUXK_ALPHA","value":"0.03125"},{"key":"DEAD_FEATURE_THRESHOLD","value":"10000000"},{"key":"USE_HADAMARD","value":"false"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["Round 20 obeys crash-recovery mode and performs a param-only K exploration run on the best working hybrid_topk proxy setup.","The first required smaller-K probe is K=64, with the rest of the stable hybrid_topk proxy configuration held fixed for interpretability.","This round is intended as the first step before a likely K=32 follow-up, unless K=64 shows an unexpected stability or quality failure that changes the plan."],"next_hypotheses":["If hybrid_topk at K=64 is stable and reasonably competitive, run the same configuration at K=32 next to complete the required smaller-K sweep.","If K=64 collapses badly or becomes unstable, keep the architecture fixed and consider a minor recovery adjustment within hybrid_topk rather than introducing a new family immediately."],"primary_variable":"k"}
research/history_archive/07_20260321_004359/logs/agent_action_0016.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"The recent hybrid and adaptive-threshold results suggest the main failure mode is not lack of an anchor but how nonlinear information is injected into support selection. A union_topk encoder that keeps the baseline linear top-k proposal intact while letting a nonlinear branch propose an alternate candidate set, with final support chosen from the union rather than from perturbed logits, could lower FVU by adding complementary features without destabilizing the proven linear path.","summary":"The orthogonality regularization follow-up regressed on both proxy FVU and throughput, so more local regularization sweeps are not justified. This round adds a new `union_topk` family under `sparsify/` and tests it first at the same K=128/ef=8/Adam anchor, probing whether branch-level candidate union is a better way to add encoder expressivity than the recent additive, gating, or suppression mechanisms.","change_type":"edit_architecture","experiment_tier":"proxy","expected_win":"lower_fvu","family_name":"union_topk","family_stage":"prototype","self_review":"This is a single coherent architecture bet that directly addresses the weakness exposed by recent edits: nonlinear branches have either interfered with or failed to improve baseline support. The risk is that merged candidate sets may still be too redundant to beat hybrid_topk, but the design preserves the strongest prior while giving the nonlinear branch a cleaner path to help.","needs_sanity":true,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"union_topk"},{"key":"K","value":"128"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"8"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"adam"}],"touched_files":["/root/sparsify-ascend/sparsify/union_topk_sparse_coder.py","/root/sparsify-ascend/sparsify/config.py","/root/sparsify-ascend/sparsify/sparse_coder.py","/root/sparsify-ascend/sparsify/__init__.py"],"notes_to_memory":["Round 16 adds a new union_topk family that preserves the linear TopK proposal and lets a nonlinear branch contribute only through alternate candidate proposals before the final global top-k.","A quick local import and forward check passed for union_topk before returning control to the runtime."],"next_hypotheses":["If union_topk shows a strong proxy gain, promote it to full as the next mainline quality candidate.","If union_topk is flat or weak, the next round should either stabilize this branch-union family with a family-specific width change or pivot to a more radical new encoder design rather than returning to recent discarded regularization ideas."]}
research/history_archive/history_20260320_152535/logs/agent_action_0009.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"At fixed K=128, a Hadamard-rotated mixture_topk SAE with a softly routed two-expert encoder will lower proxy FVU versus the current linear top-k anchor by letting different encoder experts specialize to different token regimes without the hard capacity bottlenecks and optimization friction seen in grouped routing variants.","summary":"Add a new mixture_topk prototype under sparsify/ and run it as a proxy at K=128 with Hadamard and the baseline signum optimizer. This is a quality-first architecture exploration step after factorized_topk produced a clearly weak proxy result, so the next move is a smoother higher-expressivity encoder family rather than another local sweep.","change_type":"edit_sae_code","experiment_tier":"proxy","expected_win":"lower_fvu","family_name":"mixture_topk","family_stage":"prototype","self_review":"This keeps to one coherent hypothesis, stays within sparsify/, and preserves the fixed execution layer. The new family is intentionally minimal: two soft-routed encoder experts feeding the standard fixed-K decoder path. A local instantiation plus forward/backward sanity check passed. The main risk is that soft expert averaging may collapse toward a single branch under signum, so a weak proxy result would argue for either optimizer-specific stabilization or moving on quickly.","needs_sanity":true,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"mixture_topk"},{"key":"K","value":"128"},{"key":"USE_HADAMARD","value":"1"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"}],"touched_files":["sparsify/config.py","sparsify/sparse_coder.py","sparsify/__init__.py","sparsify/mixture_topk_sparse_coder.py"],"notes_to_memory":["Read research/program.md before deciding; with factorized_topk clearly weak under normal runtime, this round should try a new quality-first encoder family rather than continue narrow local tuning.","No operator_hints were present in the structured context for this round.","Added a mixture_topk prototype that uses a soft two-expert encoder mixture before the standard fixed-K top-k selection, aiming to increase routing expressivity without hard group-capacity limits.","Local sanity check passed for mixture_topk: Python instantiation plus forward/backward succeeded on a toy tensor, so the family is compatible with the existing SparseCoder training path."],"next_hypotheses":["If mixture_topk shows promising proxy FVU, keep the family alive with a stabilization pass over optimizer or family-specific expert count/routing sharpness before considering any smaller-K search.","If mixture_topk improves quality but shows a throughput regression, follow with an edit_perf_code pass focused on the extra expert projection path instead of discarding the family.","If mixture_topk is clearly weak on proxy FVU, move on to another higher-expressivity encoder family rather than spending more rounds on local tuning around top-k."]}
research/history_archive/07_20260321_004359/logs/agent_action_0008.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"hybrid_topk has now beaten the K=128 full baseline, so the next quality-first move is to stabilize the same family with an optimizer better suited to its smooth nonlinear residual branch. Test hybrid_topk at K=128 with Adam to see whether denser adaptive updates improve FVU beyond the current full frontier.","summary":"hybrid_topk is the first family to improve the K=128 full frontier, but the gain is still small relative to the aggressive quality target. This round keeps the architecture fixed and changes only the optimizer to probe whether the family is currently undertrained rather than intrinsically capped.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"proxy","expected_win":"lower_fvu","family_name":"hybrid_topk","family_stage":"stabilize","self_review":"This is a disciplined follow-up because the family finally showed real full-run promise and deserves one quality-focused stabilization pass before opening more architectures. Adam may not help, but it tests a concrete training-dynamics hypothesis without confounding the model design.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"hybrid_topk"},{"key":"K","value":"128"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"8"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"adam"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["hybrid_topk is now the best full K=128 frontier at FVU 0.18129383772611618, narrowly beating the previous topk anchor 0.18532327562570572.","Round 8 keeps focus on hybrid_topk and tests whether Adam can better optimize its nonlinear residual branch than signum."],"next_hypotheses":["If hybrid_topk plus Adam improves proxy FVU, promote it to full as the new mainline family candidate.","If hybrid_topk plus Adam is flat or worse, keep the family but try a higher-capacity quality pass such as larger expansion_factor before considering cost reduction or lower K."]}
