research/history_archive/16_20260328_220351/round_summaries/round_0173.json:52:      "This round is a strict matched architecture probe: keep `K=128`, `EXPANSION_FACTOR=2`, `OPTIMIZER=signum`, and `LR=3.0e-3` explicitly pinned, and change only `ARCHITECTURE`.",
research/history_archive/07_20260321_004359/round_summaries/round_0005.json:56:        "key": "ARCHITECTURE",
research/history_archive/11_20260322_021455/round_summaries/round_0013.json:81:        "key": "ARCHITECTURE",
research/history_archive/16_20260328_220351/round_summaries/round_0055.json:19:    "hypothesis": "Round 54 completed the Hadamard-anchor LR localization: both adjacent callbacks around the current `gated@128` recipe (`LR=2.4e-3` in Round 53 and `LR=1.6e-3` in Round 54) stayed healthy but finished slightly worse than the `LR=2.0e-3` anchor, so the signum LR branch is now closed again. The next single question in the prescribed mainline order is therefore optimizer under the strengthened recipe: with `ARCHITECTURE=gated`, `K=128`, `EXPANSION_FACTOR=12`, `LR=2.0e-3`, and `USE_HADAMARD=1` fixed, does swapping `signum` to `adam` now produce a healthier curve or competitive FVU, or does `gated` still clearly prefer `signum` even after preprocess improved conditioning?",
research/history_archive/16_20260328_220351/round_summaries/round_0055.json:20:    "summary": "Stay on the active `gated` mainline and return to the current family reference point. Keep `ARCHITECTURE=gated`, `K=128`, `EXPANSION_FACTOR=12`, `LR=2.0e-3`, `AUXK_ALPHA=0.03125`, and `USE_HADAMARD=1` fixed, and change only `OPTIMIZER` from `signum` to `adam`. Judge this run by the full trajectory, not just the endpoint: if `adam` now avoids the old mid-training blow-up and finishes competitively against the `0.142923` signum anchor, it earns exactly one LR callback on the same Hadamard recipe next; if it is flatter, noisier, or clearly worse again, lock `signum` as the optimizer for the strengthened `gated` mainline and stop the optimizer branch.",
research/history_archive/16_20260328_220351/round_summaries/round_0055.json:29:        "key": "ARCHITECTURE",
research/history_archive/16_20260328_220351/round_summaries/round_0055.json:104:    "description": "Stay on the active `gated` mainline and return to the current family reference point. Keep `ARCHITECTURE=gated`, `K=128`, `EXPANSION_FACTOR=12`, `LR=2.0e-3`, `AUXK_ALPHA=0.03125`, and `USE_HADAMARD=1` fixed, and change only `OPTIMIZER` from `signum` to `adam`. Judge this run by the full trajectory, not just the endpoint: if `adam` now avoids the old mid-training blow-up and finishes competitively against the `0.142923` signum anchor, it earns exactly one LR callback on the same Hadamard recipe next; if it is flatter, noisier, or clearly worse again, lock `signum` as the optimizer for the strengthened `gated` mainline and stop the optimizer branch.",
research/history_archive/12_20260323_013532/logs/agent_action_0073.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"`two_stage_residual` at the refreshed low-K mainline target (`K=32`, `EF=12`) remained weak, so the next informative move is to keep that lower-K target fixed and test a different architecture that changes the access pattern itself. Run `lowrank_grouped_residual` at `K=32`, `EF=12` with the shared `signum`/`LR=1.6e-3`/`AUXK_ALPHA=0` recipe to check whether grouped residual competition yields a better low-K quality/deployment tradeoff than the recent routed and two-stage variants.","summary":"Hold the refreshed comparison target at `K=32`, `EF=12` and switch only architecture to `lowrank_grouped_residual`. This continues the stagnation-breaking search with a more structured low-K mechanism rather than another TopK-local or optimizer change.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"proxy","expected_win":"explore_unknown","family_name":"lowrank_grouped_residual","family_stage":"mainline_comparison","self_review":"This keeps the round architecture-led under severe stagnation and preserves the lower-K mainline target introduced in rounds 71-72. The main risk is that the grouped residual idea was only middling at `K=40`, `EF=8`, but refreshing it at `K=32`, `EF=12` is a cleaner read than revisiting archived families or resuming minor sweeps.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"lowrank_grouped_residual"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"12"},{"key":"K","value":"32"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"},{"key":"LR","value":"1.6e-3"},{"key":"AUXK_ALPHA","value":"0.0"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["Round 73 keeps the refreshed low-K mainline target fixed at `K=32`, `EF=12` and changes only architecture after `two_stage_residual` remained weak.","`lowrank_grouped_residual` is refreshed in the preferred mainline band to test whether more structured grouped competition improves low-K behavior relative to routed and two-stage families."],"next_hypotheses":["If `lowrank_grouped_residual` at `K=32`, `EF=12` is competitive, keep the family fixed and map `K=40` before touching EF.","If `lowrank_grouped_residual` at `K=32`, `EF=12` is still weak, pivot to another fundamentally different non-TopK direction in the same mainline band rather than reopening archived TopK-family comparisons."],"primary_variable":"architecture"}
research/history_archive/11_20260322_021455/logs/agent_action_0012.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"The current JumpReLU K=128 baseline may benefit from more aggressive signum updates, and increasing LR to 1.6e-3 could improve optimization enough to beat both the failed 4e-4 proxy and the standing 0.1888 full-FVU anchor.","summary":"Keep JumpReLU fixed at the K=128 quality anchor and continue the single-parameter LR sweep by testing 1.6e-3 next.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"proxy","expected_win":"quality","family_name":"jumprelu","family_stage":"stabilize","self_review":"This follows the planned opposite-direction LR probe after 4e-4 underperformed and keeps the round tightly scoped to one parameter. The main risk is overshooting and harming training, but the previous lower-LR result strongly suggests the baseline is not simply overstepping already.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"jumprelu"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"8"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"},{"key":"LR","value":"1.6e-3"},{"key":"AUXK_ALPHA","value":"0.03125"},{"key":"JUMPRELU_INIT_THRESHOLD","value":"0.15"},{"key":"JUMPRELU_BANDWIDTH","value":"0.1"},{"key":"K","value":"128"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["LR=4e-4 was substantially worse than the K=128 JumpReLU baseline in proxy, so lower-LR stabilization is not promising on this family at the anchor setting.","Round 12 tests the opposite LR direction at 1.6e-3 while keeping all other JumpReLU K=128 settings fixed.","This round is intended to determine whether the current baseline is limited by under-aggressive optimization rather than architecture or sparsity budget."],"next_hypotheses":["If LR=1.6e-3 improves proxy FVU, promote to full and continue LR refinement at K=128 before more auxk or expansion sweeps.","If LR=1.6e-3 is also worse, finish the LR bracket with 2e-4 or 3.2e-3 only if the result suggests a monotonic trend; otherwise move to auxk_alpha sweeps.","If LR sweeps remain unpromising, keep K=128 fixed and test AUXK_ALPHA=0 next to see whether the auxiliary objective is hurting primary reconstruction quality."],"primary_variable":"lr"}
