research/history_archive/11_20260322_021455/logs/agent_action_0038.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"The last round showed the gated low-K capacity cut was a real quality regression, and the search has now gone several rounds without advancing an incubating alternative family. The least-bad informative move is to get a real proxy read on the already-implemented `group_topk` family at K=128 under the strongest current training regime, removing the unsupported `GROUP_TOPK_SIZE` override that caused the earlier policy crashes. This will finally test whether local winner-take-all competition can beat other non-gated support selectors on anchor-quality rather than being discarded for an execution-layer mismatch.","summary":"Run the first real proxy comparison for `group_topk` at K=128 using the current strongest gated training regime, but without the unsupported `GROUP_TOPK_SIZE` env override that caused the earlier crashes.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"proxy","expected_win":"explore_unknown","family_name":"group_topk","family_stage":"prototype","self_review":"This advances an incubating family instead of spending another round on weak local gated tuning, and it specifically resolves prior `group_topk` crashes as execution-layer issues rather than architectural evidence. The main risk is that hard local competition may still be too restrictive to challenge gated on FVU, but one clean proxy run is necessary before deciding whether to retire or stabilize this family.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"group_topk"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"16"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"},{"key":"LR","value":"1.6e-3"},{"key":"AUXK_ALPHA","value":"0.01"},{"key":"K","value":"128"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["Rounds 32-33 did not provide architectural evidence on `group_topk`; they were rejected because `GROUP_TOPK_SIZE` is not an allowed execution-layer override.","This round retries `group_topk` with only allowed overrides so the family gets its first actual proxy measurement under the current strongest K=128 training regime.","Using the gated anchor settings at K=128 isolates architecture as the primary changed variable and gives a clean read on whether local competition is a viable quality direction."],"next_hypotheses":["If `group_topk` is competitive with gated at K=128, keep the family alive and follow with a code-round that softens or enriches the grouped selection mechanism inside `sparsify/`, since group-size sweeps are not exposed by the execution layer.","If `group_topk` is clearly worse on quality under a normal run, retire hard local grouping and move to a more expressive multi-branch or factorized encoder family instead of more support-ranking variants.","If `group_topk` is mediocre on FVU but materially better on runtime or memory, evaluate it as a cost-quality tradeoff family before discarding it."],"primary_variable":"architecture"}
research/history_archive/11_20260322_021455/round_summaries/round_0003.json:63:        "key": "ARCHITECTURE",
research/history_archive/11_20260322_021455/logs/agent_action_0052.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"Plain gated/local parameter sweeps have revalidated the low-K frontier but are not closing the quality gap, and the session has gone eight rounds without advancing a new family. A minimal `factorized_topk` prototype that inserts a low-rank ReLU mixing stage before hard top-k selection could improve support quality at K=128 while staying cheaper than a full dense two-branch encoder, so the next round should finally give this family a real proxy measurement under the current strongest signum regime.","summary":"Run a K=128 proxy prototype for the newly wired `factorized_topk` architecture under the current best signum settings to test whether low-rank encoder mixing can beat plain top-k/gated quality.","change_type":"edit_sae_code","experiment_tier":"proxy","expected_win":"explore_unknown","family_name":"factorized_topk","family_stage":"prototype","self_review":"This is the smallest architecture-exploration step that respects the current stability rules: the code change is confined to `sparsify/`, passes a forward/backward sanity check, and resolves the concrete registration blocker that prevented any real signal from this family. The main risk is throughput or weak quality from the unfused two-layer encoder, but that would still be informative and separable from the earlier launcher/config failure.","needs_sanity":true,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"factorized_topk"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"16"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"},{"key":"LR","value":"1.6e-3"},{"key":"AUXK_ALPHA","value":"0.01"},{"key":"K","value":"128"}],"touched_files":["sparsify/config.py","sparsify/sparse_coder.py"],"notes_to_memory":["Registered `factorized_topk` in `SparseCoderConfig` validation and SAE class dispatch so the execution layer can actually launch the family.","Implemented a minimal `factorized_topk` prototype with a low-rank ReLU mixing stage before latent scoring; hidden width is derived from existing config (`max(d_in/2, 4*K)`) so no launcher changes are required.","Local forward/backward sanity passed for `factorized_topk` at K=128, so the prior failure mode was a code-integration blocker rather than an architecture-quality result."],"next_hypotheses":["If `factorized_topk` completes and shows promising proxy FVU, keep the family alive and stabilize its internal width/throughput tradeoff next.","If it runs but is clearly worse than gated and plain top-k, archive this shallow factorized path and move to a different encoder-expressivity family.","If quality is plausible but runtime is poor, follow with an `edit_perf_code` round focused on the factorized encoder path rather than discarding the family."],"primary_variable":"architecture"}
research/history_archive/11_20260322_021455/logs/agent_action_0041.json:1:{"change_type":"edit_perf_code","command":"run","env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"group_topk"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"16"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"},{"key":"LR","value":"1.6e-3"},{"key":"AUXK_ALPHA","value":"0.01"},{"key":"K","value":"128"}],"expected_win":"explore_unknown","experiment_tier":"proxy","family_name":"group_topk","family_stage":"prototype","hypothesis":"The recent `first_step_timeout` crashes are not specific to `group_topk`: the gated AUXK=0 recovery run also advanced through the first few microbatches and then stalled at the first optimizer step. That points to a shared training-path bottleneck rather than an architecture verdict. Replacing CUDA's per-step fired-latent `cat`+advanced-index update with an incremental boolean fired mask in `sparsify/trainer.py` should remove that first-step spike and let the unresolved `group_topk` K=128 proxy run complete under the current strongest regime.","needs_sanity":true,"next_hypotheses":["If the patched `group_topk` run completes and is competitive with gated at K=128, keep the family alive and start stabilizing its grouped-selection design inside `sparsify/`.","If the run completes normally but `group_topk` is still clearly worse on FVU, retire hard grouped competition and move to a more expressive new family rather than more selector variants.","If `group_topk` still hits a first-step timeout after this shared trainer fix, stop spending rounds on it and treat the remaining issue as a deeper execution-path incompatibility."],"notes_to_memory":["Rounds 38 and 40 both progressed through several microbatches before timing out, so the failure signature is now shared across `group_topk` and gated rather than isolated to one family.","The stall aligns with the first optimizer step, which makes shared post-accumulation bookkeeping a stronger suspect than encoder forward quality.","This round patches `sparsify/trainer.py` so CUDA tracks fired latents with an incremental per-step boolean mask instead of building a large concatenated index tensor at step end, while preserving the deferred NPU path."],"primary_variable":"code_fix","self_review":"This is the narrowest defensible follow-up because the unresolved issue is now a shared runtime bottleneck, and another parameter-only probe would risk repeating the same crash without adding architectural evidence. The main risk is that the timeout may come from optimizer or logging overhead instead, but the logs make the fired-latent bookkeeping on the first optimizer step the best current target.","summary":"Patch the shared trainer dead-feature bookkeeping to reduce first-optimizer-step overhead on CUDA, then retry the blocked `group_topk` K=128 proxy comparison under the gated anchor settings.","touched_files":["sparsify/trainer.py"]}
research/history_archive/11_20260322_021455/round_summaries/round_0064.json:101:        "key": "ARCHITECTURE",
