research/history_archive/16_20260328_220351/round_summaries/round_0199.json:18:    "summary": "Run one matched architecture probe with ARCHITECTURE=lowrank_asymmetric_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual while keeping K=128, EF=2, signum, and LR=3.0e-3 fixed. It is LUTurbo \u6269\u5c55\u517c\u5bb9 with reconstruction x_hat = U(Vx) + \u03a3_m pi_m c_m + \u03a3_i alpha_i^(1) b_i + \u03a3_j alpha_j^(2) b_j, and it is the nearest feasible architecture variant to the current mainline without adding extra encoder-cost/routing overhead.",
research/history_archive/16_20260328_220351/round_summaries/round_0199.json:27:        "key": "ARCHITECTURE",
research/history_archive/11_20260322_021455/logs/agent_action_0061.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"Local gated sweeps have restored the stable baseline but are not closing the quality gap, and the most concrete unresolved blocker is still that `residual_topk` cannot be selected by the execution layer. The least-bad informative move is a narrow code round that registers and wires `residual_topk` into `SparseCoderConfig` validation and SAE class dispatch so the intended K=128 proxy prototype can finally produce a real quality signal.","summary":"Add `residual_topk` support under `sparsify/` and rerun the same K=128 proxy prototype under the existing signum regime.","change_type":"edit_sae_code","experiment_tier":"proxy","expected_win":"explore_unknown","family_name":"residual_topk","family_stage":"prototype","self_review":"This follows the operator guidance to fix architecture-specific blockers before drawing quality conclusions, and it keeps the round focused on a single variable: making the blocked family runnable. The main risk is that registration is not the only incompatibility, but even that outcome is more informative than spending another round on incremental gated tuning.","needs_sanity":true,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"residual_topk"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"16"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"},{"key":"LR","value":"1.6e-3"},{"key":"AUXK_ALPHA","value":"0.01"},{"key":"K","value":"128"}],"touched_files":["sparsify/config.py","sparsify/sparse_coder.py"],"notes_to_memory":["The runtime policy still says quality is the primary objective, but recent gated param-only rounds are now yielding only marginal frontier movement rather than a step-change toward the aggressive FVU target.","`residual_topk` remains untested on quality because its recent failures were architecture-registration crashes in `sparsify/`, which should be treated as implementation blockers rather than evidence against the family.","This round should change only the SAE code needed to make `residual_topk` selectable and runnable by the existing launcher, keeping the prototype hyperparameters otherwise fixed."],"next_hypotheses":["If `residual_topk` runs and shows competitive proxy FVU, keep the family alive and stabilize its internal budget split next.","If `residual_topk` runs cleanly but is clearly worse than gated and not better than prior incubating families, archive it quickly and resume broader architecture exploration.","If `residual_topk` still fails after registration and dispatch are fixed, treat the remaining issue as a deeper implementation incompatibility and move to a different new family rather than continue local gated sweeps."],"primary_variable":"code_fix"}
research/history_archive/12_20260323_013532/logs/agent_action_0046.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"`lowrank_gated_residual` has now produced a smooth chain of valid lower-K full points through `K=56`, so the remaining high-value question is how much farther this family can extend the Pareto frontier below the old `K=64` anchor before quality bends too sharply. A proxy probe at `K=48` on the unchanged recipe is the cleanest next step to test that lower-K boundary while staying within the strongest validated family and same-EF comparison regime.","summary":"Run a parameter-only proxy experiment for `lowrank_gated_residual` at `K=48`, keeping `EF=32`, `signum`, `LR=1.6e-3`, and `AUXK_ALPHA=0.0` fixed. This continues the prioritized lower-K frontier sweep below the new `K=56` point without mixing in architecture or capacity changes.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"proxy","expected_win":"smaller_k","family_name":"lowrank_gated_residual","family_stage":"mainline","self_review":"This keeps the session on a conservative K-only track instead of pivoting to a new family. That is justified because `K=56` still held up as a real full frontier point, so one more lower-K probe is more informative than reopening EF or architecture immediately. Main risk: `K=48` may regress enough that it only confirms the boundary rather than adding a useful new Pareto point.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"lowrank_gated_residual"},{"key":"K","value":"48"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"32"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"},{"key":"LR","value":"1.6e-3"},{"key":"AUXK_ALPHA","value":"0.0"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["Round 45 full confirmed `K=56` as a valid lower-K frontier point for `lowrank_gated_residual`, so the next informative move is to continue probing the lower-K boundary rather than changing EF.","`K=48` is the next clean same-family, same-EF test below `K=56` to measure whether this family can keep extending the Pareto frontier before architecture search resumes."],"next_hypotheses":["If `K=48` is promoted and full remains reasonably close to the `K=56` point, keep it as another smaller-K Pareto point and consider one final lower-K probe.","If `K=48` regresses sharply, pivot next to a same-EF architecture comparison or a new family rather than pushing K lower in this family."],"primary_variable":"k"}
research/history_archive/11_20260322_021455/logs/agent_action_0007.json:1:{"change_type":"edit_sae_code","command":"run","env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"gated"}],"expected_win":"explore_unknown","experiment_tier":"proxy","family_name":"gated","family_stage":"prototype","hypothesis":"A gated SAE that decouples latent support selection from reconstruction magnitude can beat the current JumpReLU anchor at K=128 by learning a separate sigmoid routing branch while staying initialization-close to plain ReLU top-k.","needs_sanity":true,"next_hypotheses":["If gated shows better proxy FVU at acceptable throughput, stabilize the family by exposing and tuning gate temperature/init strength in a follow-up.","If gated quality is promising but throughput regresses, keep the family alive and do a performance-focused follow-up rather than discarding the architecture.","If gated fails to improve proxy FVU, move on to a different routing-focused family instead of more JumpReLU-local sweeps."],"notes_to_memory":["Added a new `gated` SAE family under `sparsify/` with a second encoder branch that produces sigmoid gates for support selection.","The gate branch is initialized with zero weights and a positive bias so the prototype starts close to plain ReLU top-k rather than an aggressively sparse regime.","Current execution-layer hooks do not expose gated-specific env knobs, so this first prototype relies on default `gated_temperature=1.0` and `gated_init_logit=2.0`."],"primary_variable":"architecture","self_review":"This is a clean single-family prototype and respects the proxy-first policy, but it adds a second encoder matmul so throughput may regress; that risk is acceptable for one exploratory proxy round because recent local JumpReLU tuning already failed.","summary":"Prototype a new `gated` architecture at the K=128 anchor by adding a separate sigmoid routing branch, keeping all other launch settings at baseline so the round cleanly measures whether decoupled support selection can open a better quality regime than JumpReLU.","touched_files":["/root/sparsify-ascend/sparsify/config.py","/root/sparsify-ascend/sparsify/sparse_coder.py"]}
research/history_archive/11_20260322_021455/round_summaries/round_0022.json:57:        "key": "ARCHITECTURE",
research/history_archive/11_20260322_021455/logs/agent_action_0008.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"A softer JumpReLU gate may recover stable throughput and improve proxy FVU versus the failed sharp-gating attempt by widening the bandwidth around the current best K=128 anchor without changing architecture or optimizer.","summary":"Stay on the best known working JumpReLU K=128 configuration and run a single softer-gating proxy check by increasing gate bandwidth slightly, keeping the round focused on stability recovery and a clean read on threshold dynamics.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"proxy","expected_win":"quality","family_name":"jumprelu","family_stage":"stabilize","self_review":"This stays within crash-recovery constraints and makes only a minor parameter adjustment on the current best working family. The main risk is that bandwidth softening may be too small to move FVU materially, but it is the safest informative step after consecutive crashes and the prior perf regression.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"jumprelu"},{"key":"JUMPRELU_INIT_THRESHOLD","value":"0.15"},{"key":"JUMPRELU_BANDWIDTH","value":"0.15"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["Round 8 used crash-recovery param-only mode and stayed on the best working JumpReLU K=128 anchor.","Tested a softer JumpReLU gate by widening bandwidth from 0.1 to 0.15 while keeping the threshold at 0.15 to separate stability effects from architecture changes.","This round is intended to check whether the round-3 regression came from overly sharp gating rather than from JumpReLU itself."],"next_hypotheses":["If wider-bandwidth JumpReLU improves proxy FVU with normal throughput, continue stabilizing within JumpReLU with another small gate-shape adjustment before any K reduction.","If throughput recovers but quality is flat or worse, try a small LR adjustment on the best JumpReLU anchor rather than more aggressive threshold changes.","If this softer-gating proxy still underperforms, pause JumpReLU-local sweeps until crash recovery ends and then revisit broader architecture exploration."],"primary_variable":"other_param"}
